  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Researchers are increasingly interested in multi-dimensional properties of words.",
    "For example, the Lancaster sensorimotor norms contain judgments about the extent to which six sensory modalities and five action effectors are associated with different words (Lynott et al., 2020); these norms, along with others (Binder et al., 2016), offer a degree of granularity and semantic nuance that is much harder to achieve with a single dimension.",
    "Yet as more dimensions of interest are added, the problem of scale compounds.",
    "Returning to the example above: if a researcher needs ten judgments for 11 different dimensions of 40,000 words, which amounts to 4,400,00 judgments in total.",
    "Sub-problem #2: Context."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For example, the Lancaster sensorimotor norms contain judgments about the extent to which six sensory modalities and five action effectors are associated with different words (Lynott et al., 2020); these norms, along with others (Binder et al., 2016), offer a degree of granularity and semantic nuance that is much harder to achieve with a single dimension."
